   <text>
      <body>
         <div type="letter">
            <pb n="1" facs="uoedh_hl_h.700_1.jpg"/>
            <note rend="red pencil" hand="unknown">Capt. Acland M.S. of "<ref
                  target="#bib:Hardy1886_Mayor"><emph rend="italics">The Mayor of
                     Casterbridge</emph></ref>"</note>
            <opener>


               <address rend="letterhead">
                  <addrLine>Dorset County Museum</addrLine>
                  <addrLine>Dorchester</addrLine>

               </address>
               <dateline>
                  <date when="1911-11-14">14<hi rend="superscript">th</hi> Nov<hi rend="superscript"
                        >r</hi> 1911</date>
               </dateline>
               <!-- on dotted line -->

               <salute rend="typescript"> Sir,</salute>

            </opener>

            <p rend="typescript"> On behalf of the Council of <orgName ref="#ps:DorsetCountyMuseum"
                  >Dorset County Museum</orgName>, I beg to thank you for your valuable gift of <!-- dotted line begins -->
               <handShift rend="black pen"/> your original <choice><abbr>M.S.</abbr>
                  <expan>manuscript</expan></choice> of <ref target="#bib:Hardy1886_Mayor">"The
                  Mayor of Casterbridge"</ref>
               <handShift rend="typescript"/> which will be submitted to the Council for acceptance
               at the next meeting. </p>



            <closer>
               <salute>I remain,</salute>
               <salute>Yours faithfully,</salute>
               <signed>John E. Acland</signed>
               <!-- handwritten --> Curator. </closer>

            <postscript rend="black pen">

               <opener>
                  <handShift/> Dear M<hi rend="superscript">r</hi> Hardy</opener>
               <p> Your gift is even better than I expected, if I may <pb n="2"
                     facs="uoedh_hl_h.700_2.jpg"/> say so, and will be very greatly valued, &amp;
                  safely preserved. </p>

               <p>I am looking forward with much pleasure to the play tomorrow night.</p>

               <p>I have found out from <persName ref="#ps:WilliamBarnes"><choice>
                        <abbr>Rev.</abbr>
                        <expan>Reverend</expan></choice> W. Miles Barnes</persName>, that all the
                  poets <choice><abbr>M. S.</abbr>
                     <expan>manuscripts</expan></choice> were disposed of after the time of his
                  death.</p>

               <closer>
                  <salute><choice><abbr>Yrs</abbr>
                        <expan>Yours</expan></choice> very truly</salute>
                  <signed>John E. Acland</signed>
               </closer>
            </postscript>


         </div>
